## Hiding Complex Content from Slides

Use **`.transcript-only`** to hide content that doesn't work well in slide format:

### When to Hide Content

**Complex tables with many columns:**

```asciidoc
[.slide]
== Filtering query logs

[.transcript-only]
====
You can filter query logs by the following criteria:
====

[cols="2,4,1,3", options="header"]
|===
| Filter | Description | Type | Example
... detailed table ...
|===
```

**Detailed tip boxes:**

```asciidoc
[TIP,role=transcript-only]
.Setting a custom application name
====
Detailed code examples and explanations...
====
```

**Why hide this content:**

- Complex tables are hard to read on slides - discuss verbally instead
- Detailed tip boxes distract from main teaching points
- Code examples in tips are better in transcript for reference
- Keeps slides focused on key concepts for instructor presentation

## When NOT to Use Slides

Do not apply slide formatting to:

- **Challenge lessons** (`:type: challenge` in frontmatter) - these are for learners to read independently
- Quiz sections (marked with `[.quiz]`)
- Summary sections (marked with `[.summary]`)
- Questions includes (these have their own formatting)
- Collapsible content blocks (`[%collapsible]`)

## Migration Checklist

When converting existing content to slides:

- [ ] **Check lesson type**: Only apply slides to `:type: lesson` - SKIP `:type: challenge` lessons entirely
- [ ] Identify natural content breaks (one concept per slide)
- [ ] Mark text-only sections with `[.slide]`
- [ ] Check each image aspect ratio and content length
- [ ] Apply `[.slide.col-2]` or `[.slide.col-2.reverse]` for images (even wide ones work)
- [ ] Consider `.reverse` when image provides essential context that should appear first in linear flow
- [ ] Decide if subsections should be full `[.slide]` (for navigation) or `[.slide.discrete]` (hidden from TOC)
- [ ] Wrap complex tables in `[.transcript-only]` blocks if they don't present well on slides
- [ ] Mark detailed tips as `[TIP,role=transcript-only]` if they're better for reading
- [ ] Consider `[.slide.col-2]` for two related text subsections that complement each other
- [ ] Test rendered 16:9 output for balance and readability
- [ ] Verify images remain readable when displayed in columns
- [ ] Ensure consistency across the entire lesson
